The standard way to report progress is to use the [`IProgress&lt;T&gt;`][1] interface. There is already an implementation of this interface that you can use ([`Progress&lt;T&gt;`][2]), and is generic so that you can supply any type of argument you want. In the example bellow the argument is a `string`. The key point is that the event [`Progress.ProgressChanged`][3] is running in the UI thread, so you don&#39;t have to worry about it.

    // This will run in the UI thread
    private async void Export_Execute_Click(object sender, EventArgs args)
    {
        try
        {
